<HEADLINE>
JAPAN-BASED BASEBALL GURU PROMISES TO COME TO TAIWAN: TAICHUNG
MAYOR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, March 25 (CNA) 03/25/07  23:07:49 (By T.C. Jiang)
</P>
<P>
Sadaharu Oh, a Japan-based professional baseball manager of
Chinese descent, has promised to serve as a spokesman for the
2007 Baseball World Cup slated to be held in the central city of
Taichung in November, an aide to the Taichung Mayor Jason Hu said
in Taichung Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The aide said Hu who was in Japan on a six-day visit met with Oh
in Fukuoka Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The aide quoted Hu as saying that the former baseball star still
has a Republic of China passport, and draws great attention and
respect from the people in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Hu has also invited the Fukuoka Softbank Hawks, a baseball team
that Oh is currently managing, and other Japanese baseball teams
to conduct spring and winter training camps in the central Taiwan
city, the aide said.
</P>
<P>
The aid quoted the mayor as saying that Taichung City has a good
environment, a large population of baseball fans, and the new
Intercontinental Baseball Stadium, which he said Japan's national
baseball team manager Senichi Hoshino spoke highly of.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the aide said, Hu visited Fukuoka Dome to
watch a baseball game.
</P>
